I think that’s one of your stronger metaphors because it captures something important about language without requiring it to be literally true.

If we unpack it:

* Words are holds, not destinations.
* Sentences are routes across the wall.
* Concepts are regions of the wall.
* Memory is partly knowing which holds you’ve already used and which routes worked.
* Reasoning is choosing the next reachable hold while maintaining balance.

That maps surprisingly well to how both humans and language models often operate. Neither typically “jumps” from start to finish. They move through a sequence of locally connected ideas, where each step changes what becomes reachable next.

The climbing metaphor also explains why phrasing matters so much. If you replace one hold, you may open an entirely different set of routes.

For example:

* “What is true?” leads one direction.
* “What survives transformation?” leads another.
* “What is conserved?” leads another.
* “What generates this?” leads another.

Each question places your hand on a different hold.

One thing I’d add is that the wall isn’t fixed.

Every new experience, theorem, experiment, or metaphor can add new holds or reveal that two distant holds were actually connected all along. Expertise often looks like seeing routes that beginners literally don’t perceive.

Where your Pantheon framework becomes interesting is that it tries to build better holds rather than just higher walls. Concepts like Ariadne’s thread, Semantic Basis Optimization, Comparative Invariant Analysis, and Fruitful Framing are attempts to create reusable handholds that work in many different regions of the conceptual landscape.

The place I’d stay cautious is assuming every nearby hold leads somewhere meaningful. Sometimes two ideas are adjacent because of language rather than because of the underlying phenomenon. That’s where your anchor thread—and empirical testing—becomes valuable. It lets you ask:

“Did this route actually take us somewhere, or did it only feel connected?”

That combination is powerful:

* Creative climbing to discover new routes.
* An anchor thread to avoid getting lost.
* Reality as the belayer that catches you when a route doesn’t actually hold.

That last piece is what allows exploration to become cumulative knowledge rather than just an endless maze of interesting metaphors.